properties.description: A prestigious Grade II listed building. Opened in 1939 by Imperial Airways and subsequently used by BOAC and then British Airways. The building has been the home of the National Audit Office since 1986 and was refurbished in 2009.
properties.name: National Audit Office

properties.description: Beautiful mausoleum in former Royal Navy cemetery, restored 1999 by the University of Greenwich. Many interesting plaques and grave stones.
properties.name: Devonport Mausoleum

properties.description: We're excited to open up our London campus as part of Open House Festival. Foster + Partners is a global studio for sustainable architecture, urbanism, engineering and design, founded by Norman Foster in 1967. With offices across the world, the practice works as a single entity that is both ethnically and culturally diverse, with people central to all our endeavours.
properties.name: Foster + Partners

properties.description: Best preserved 17C schoolroom in the country. Wainscot panelling, benches, tables and chairs. Original fireplace replaced in 1730, oriel window inserted in 1820. Walls carved with names of every Harrow pupil until 1847.
properties.name: Harrow School: Old Schools, Fourth Form Room

properties.description: Opened by the Queen in 2002 as one of the first new livery halls in the Square Mile for nearly 40 years, this is a brick building with traditional lime mortar and handsome lead roof, standing around a peaceful courtyard.
properties.name: Haberdashers' Hall

properties.description: Founded to house the widows of clergymen, the original building consisted of 20 houses built around a classically-styled quadrangle. Captain Richard Ryder – one of Sir Christopher Wren's surveyors – was in charge of design and construction.
properties.name: Bromley and Sheppard's College

properties.description: Highgate is three schools in one. Founded by Sir Roger Cholmeley, Lord Chief Justice of England, in 1565, Highgate is governed as a single charitable foundation.
properties.name: Highgate School Chapel, Library, Museum

properties.description: Fine stuccoed building overlooking Pond Square, and home to Institution since 1840. Formed from 1790 coach house, stables and yard, with final additions c1880. Guided tours will be available.
properties.name: Highgate Literary & Scientific Institution

properties.description: A sumptuous feast of Victorian stained glass & bold sacred sculpture in what Sir John Betjeman called the 'cathedral of the Arts and Crafts movement.' Work by William Morris, Edward Burne-Jones, William Blake Richamind & Christopher Whall.
properties.name: Holy Trinity Church Sloane Square

properties.description: Built during the golden era of Camden public housing under Borough Architect Sydney Cook. Peter Tábori  studied with Ernő Goldfinger and worked with Denys Lasdun, and met Ken Adie when both were students at the Regent Street Polytechnic.
properties.name: 8 Stoneleigh Terrace (Highgate New Town, Stage 1)

properties.description: 1939 Art Deco Grade II listed building refurbished in 1950, then restructured and modernised in 2014. Contains an authentically classic cinema, private salons and multimedia library.
properties.name: Institut français du Royaume-Uni

properties.description: Grade I listed 1934 residential block of flats in Hampstead, designed by the Canadian modernist architect Wells Coates for clients Jack and Molly Pritchard. English Heritage blue plaque for Bauhaus masters Gropius, Breuer and Moholy-Nagy.
properties.name: Isokon Building (Lawn Road Flats)

properties.description: Adjoining Grade II listed Carnegie-funded library, museum and art gallery. Museum holdings range from ceramics to topographical drawings, including the collection left by Eadweard Muybridge, a native of Kingston and photographic pioneer.
properties.name: Kingston Library, Museum and Art Gallery

properties.description:
Abbey Mills pumping station 'A', built by engineer Joseph Bazalgette, Edmund Cooper and architect Charles Driver. Built between 1865 and 1868 it is described as the cathedral of sewage.
Follow this link to book: https://bit.ly/abbeymills
properties.name: Abbey Mills Pumping Station

properties.description: Wren-designed building completed under the direction of Hawksmoor and Vanbrugh, 1698-1712. Original wood panelling, refurbished by Dannatt Johnson in 2001 for University of Greenwich.
properties.name: Old Royal Naval College - King William Court

properties.description: London's first fireproof building, built to house records of the Court of Chancery. Now renovated to house a fine university library.
properties.name: King's College London, The Maughan Library

properties.description: Commissioned in 1825 by the Duke of York and named York House.  In 1829 the lease was purchased by the first Duke of Sutherland.  In 1913, Lord Leverhulme, bought the lease for the nation and Stafford House became Lancaster House.
properties.name: Lancaster House

properties.description: RIBA award-winning building.  Part listed frontage with purpose built archive and exhibition building added to the rear in 2002. The building now houses the University's Special Collections & Archives
properties.name: The Wash Houses

properties.description: Grade II listed ice well and underground chambers (1770) in Manor House Gardens park, which provided ice for nearby Manor House. Cited in 2002 Civic Trust Awards.
properties.name: Manor House Gardens Ice House

properties.description: The official residence of the Lord Mayor of the City of London, retaining its 18C character, with superb plasterwork and wood carving.
properties.name: Mansion House

properties.description:
A masterpiece of Victorian engineering, Markfield Beam Engine provided a vital public health facility from 1855-1964. 

On 17 & 18 Sept the 1888 beam engine will be steaming as follows:
12.30 - 1.15pm 
2.00 - 2.45pm 
3.30 - 4.15pm
properties.name: Markfield Beam Engine and House

properties.description: Grade I listed, late Georgian sugar warehouse now housing the Museum of London Docklands. Sensitively restored, the new multimedia displays coexist with the massive timber and brick structures of the original building.
properties.name: Museum of London Docklands

properties.description: Formerly boardroom of the 17C water house, the Oak Room is a fine late Renaissance room demonstrating the New River Company's wealth. Booking link: https://bit.ly/OakRooms
properties.name: Oak Room, New River Head

properties.description: Grade I listed country house commanding the most extensive southerly views over Essex. Staircase mural by Sir James Thornhill, a painter notable for the 'Painted Hall' at the Royal Naval Hospital at Greenwich. Set in grounds with a pond.
properties.name: Bower House

properties.description: Purpose built room intended for the teaching of public speaking which figured prominently in the classical curriculum. Converted 1976 by Alan Irvine into modern gallery with mezzanine floor.
properties.name: Harrow School: Old Speech Room Gallery

properties.description: A unique modern courtyard house making brilliant use of a restricted site. A retractable glass roof gives wonderful natural light and opens the house to the sky in dry weather.
properties.name: Paxton Locher House

properties.description: Described as 'the most significant church built after the WWII in Britain' - Brutalist, inclusive and influential signpost for future church design.
properties.name: St Paul's Bow Common

properties.description: Conversion of a canalside Victorian warehouse, formerly a terrazzo factory, into spacious offices, garden and glazed extension with one of the best waterside views in London. Refurbished, 2022.
properties.name: Pollard Thomas Edwards - Diespeker Wharf

properties.description: Red brick and Bath stone grand 'Elizabethan Renaissance' style building altered by war, political changes and reflecting Richmond's history.
properties.name: The Old Town Hall, Richmond

properties.description:
UPDATED: Open daily 10.30am-4pm. Closed Mon 19 September.
Guided tours 12.15pm & 1.15pm on Tuesdays, Thursdays, Fridays, Saturdays & Sundays, see below.
Home of the City of London's art collection, & remains of London's Roman Amphitheatre
properties.name: Guildhall Art Gallery

properties.description: Grade II listed, this is the oldest Quaker meeting house in London. Built in 1778, it has original panelling & a minister's gallery. See flagstones from the earlier 1674 buildings. Also a secluded burial ground & garden. Free refreshments.
properties.name: Quaker Meeting House - Wandsworth

properties.description: Wren and Hawksmoor building, completed 1749 when Thomas Ripley built the pavilions facing the river. Highlights include council boardroom, grand staircase and restored Portland stonework. Refurbished in 2000 for University of Greenwich.
properties.name: Old Royal Naval College - Queen Anne Court

properties.description: Last major building on the site (1751). Original layout, timber panelling, barrel vaulting and Portland stone. Refurbished in 2000 by Dannatt Johnson for University of Greenwich.
properties.name: Old Royal Naval College - Queen Mary Court

properties.description: Built as a Whig gentleman's club and inspired by Italian Renaissance palaces. Lobby leads to an enclosed colonnaded courtyard with complementary glazed roof and tessellated floor. Tunnelled staircase leads to upper floor.
properties.name: Reform Club

properties.description: Discover a new side of the Royal Academy of Arts, including hidden spaces not usually open to the public.
properties.name: Burlington House: Royal Academy of Arts

properties.description: Street's masterpiece and one of Victorian London's great public buildings. 13C Gothic given a Victorian interpretation.
properties.name: Royal Courts of Justice

properties.description: Numbered amongst the UK's architectural glories and boasting 66 acres of beautiful grounds, the Royal Hospital Chelsea has been home to the iconic Army veteran community fondly known as the 'Chelsea Pensioners' since its foundation in 1692.
properties.name: Royal Hospital Chelsea, Home of the Chelsea Pensioners

properties.description: Grade II listed arms factory closed to public for 170 years. Museum and clocktower open for tours.
properties.name: Royal Small Arms Factory

properties.description: Europe’s first traditional Hindu temple is a masterpiece of exquisite Indian craftsmanship. Using 5,000 tonnes of Italian and Indian marble and the finest Bulgarian limestone, it was hand-carved in India before being assembled in London.
properties.name: BAPS Shri Swaminarayan Mandir

properties.description: Guided tours of the Triforium space to see: items from the cathedral collections including Christopher Wren’s magnificent ‘Great Model’ made in 1673; the Geometrical Staircase and the stunning view from the West Gallery.
properties.name: St Paul's Cathedral - Triforium Tour

properties.description: Grade I listed, remaining tower of medieval parish church, with working late 16C clock. New exhibition of Hackney's history. Extensive views from roof. (Organised by Hackney Historic Buildings Trust).
properties.name: St Augustine's Tower

properties.description:
Convent in 18C Grade II listed house, c1764-1792, with original features including fine decorative plasterwork. Various additions including west wing (1913-15), and harmonious care home facilities and chapel by PRP Architects (1998-2001).
Apologies to visitors turned away last year. Please book for this year.
properties.name: St Mary's Convent

properties.description: A most important house in Ickenham an outstanding example of Jacobean architecture built in the 1630s. Red brick construction laid in English bond on an H plan. Great Hall includes the 1655 Harrington Screen, 18C marble fireplace panelling.
properties.name: Swakeleys Estate

properties.description: Temple Bar is a 350 year old gateway to the City of London, designed by Sir Christopher Wren. It formerly stood in Fleet Street, and was the last surviving gateway to the City of London.
properties.name: Temple Bar

properties.description: 1713 terraced house with 1914 hall at rear. Notable renovated Arts and Crafts interior. Newly refurbished glass vaulted courtyard. Portraits of Guild Masters since 1884.
properties.name: Table Top Museums at the Art Workers' Guild

properties.description: The museum is part of the Bank of England rebuilding in the 1930's by Sir Herbert Baker. One room is a reconstruction of 1793 Bank of England Stock Office by Sir John Soane.
properties.name: Bank of England Museum

properties.description: Founded c1145 by the Abbess of Barking as a hospice for thirteen old and infirm men, the present building is 12C and 19C. Grade II* listed with many interesting monuments, including Burne-Jones windows.
properties.name: The Hospital Chapel of St Mary & St Thomas

properties.description: During the Open House Festival people will have the unique opportunity to visit and explore the historic mansion and enjoy live performance throughout the day.
properties.name: Argentine Ambassador's Residence

properties.description: The world's oldest active biological society. Founded in 1788, the Society takes its name from the Swedish naturalist Carl Linnaeus whose botanical, zoological and library collections have been in its keeping since 1829.
properties.name: Burlington House: Linnean Society of London

properties.description: Grade II* listed. Built as a playhouse and entertaining audiences for over 100 years. An original Victorian auditorium with beautiful Frank Matcham interior with state-of the-art backstage and front of house facilities.
properties.name: Theatre Royal Stratford East

properties.description: A spectacular Grade I listed building designed by famed architect John Nash. Built in 1831, these former townhouses have undergone refurbishments throughout their history. The building is now home to the UK's national science academy.
properties.name: The Royal Society

properties.description: Grade II listed building by renowned Modernist which has been refurbished and remodelled whilst protecting the building's landmark status.
properties.name: Swiss Cottage Library

properties.description: One of London's hidden Modernist gems. Lubetkin's motto 'Nothing is too good for ordinary people' resonates through this building.
properties.name: Bevin Court

properties.description: Life and death in the archives, 1123-2023, is a unique exhibition detailing St Bartholomew’s Hospital's history and people, using photography, art and history from our archives and collections
properties.name: Outdoor exhibition celebrating the 900th anniversary of St Bartholomew’s Hospital - Life and death in the archives, 1123-2023

properties.description: The University of Westminster was one of the first polytechnics in the UK. Founded in 1838 as the Royal Polytechnic Institution, it was established to educate the working people of London, regardless of background or financial status.
properties.name: University of Westminster

properties.description: The recently automated impounding station controls the water level in the docks using the original Worthington Simpson pumps driven by Lancashire dynamo.
properties.name: West India Dock Impounding Station

properties.description: Grade I listed Georgian house, the only surviving home of Benjamin Franklin, retaining many original features including central staircase, lathing, 18th Century panelling, stoves, windows, fittings and beams.
properties.name: Benjamin Franklin House

properties.description: Residence of Sir Francis Ronalds, George MacDonald and (from 1878-96) William Morris. Organised by William Morris Society. Access to The William Morris Society's premises in the Coach House and basement only, includes current exhibition.
properties.name: William Morris Society - Kelmscott House

properties.description: Rare example of a hollow post mill (1817). Grade II* listed, it now contains a museum depicting the history and development of windmills in Britain. Many working models, windmill machinery, equipment and tools.
properties.name: Wimbledon Windmill

properties.description: Grade II* listed church with ragstone tower, spire, good stained glass by Kempe and recently restored William Hill organ. A characteristic work of Scott. It is Gothic Revival in the style of the 13C.
properties.name: Christ Church

properties.description: Fine Victorian church with large mosaic and painted reredos, screen and wall paintings and some unusual glass. Arts and crafts decoration by Nathaniel Westlake and Salviati Bros.
properties.name: Church of the Annunciation

properties.description: Meticulous 1930s rebuilding (complete with original furnishings) of an 1840s Marylebone church. Grade I listed. Contains works by Pugin, Burges, Street, Pearson and Butterfield.
properties.name: St Andrew's Kingsbury (new church)

properties.description:
Opportunity to hear a description and watch a demonstration of bell ringing (on Saturday only).
Church built by architect of Mansion House and contains London's oldest organ.
properties.name: Bells and Belfries at St Botolph Aldgate

properties.description: Grade I listed 12C church, with London's largest churchyard and one of the best-preserved Norman archways in the country, as well as other interesting features, including an anchorite's cell and 750-year-old wall paintings.
properties.name: St Mary Magdalene Church & Nature Reserve

properties.description: Modern architecture church with large copper and lead roof and concrete, brick and stained glass external structure. Marble, wood and plaster interior and artwork by Sculptor Freda Pinto and Gerald Holtom.
properties.name: St Paul's, Newington

properties.description: Tudor Manor House built for Sir William Compton in 1514, substantially altered in 17C, 18C & 19C. A museum since 1906 housing local history and community collections, archives, art & exhibitions of Bruce Castle, and Haringey area.
properties.name: Bruce Castle Museum

properties.description: 10 Downing Street has been the residence of British Prime Ministers since 1735. Behind its famous black door the most important decisions affecting Britain for the last 284 years have been taken.
properties.name: 10 Downing Street

properties.description: Livery Hall first built in 1429, much altered then demolished and rebuilt in 1880, destroyed in 1941 except for external walls (W W Pocock). Designed as a showpiece for the craft of carpentry, the third Hall on the site.
properties.name: Carpenters' Hall

properties.description: An important example of 1960s comprehensive school design in the Brutalist style. Acland Burghley has recently received support from the National Lottery Heritage Fund for its ambitious ‘A Hall for All’ project and have welcomed in a resident orchestra, the Orchestra of the Age of Enlightenment in a collaborative partnership which is a UK-first.
properties.name: Acland Burghley School

properties.description: Grade I listed Modernist apartment blocks retaining many original features.
properties.name: Highpoint

properties.description: Experience the history, architecture and science of the East Wing of Burlington House, home to the Royal Society of Chemistry. Part of the quadrangle extension to Burlington House, it was purpose built for the learned society.
properties.name: Burlington House: Royal Society of Chemistry

properties.description: A unique ex-carpenters' workshop (1910), contained within a working police station. The workshop space now displays a history of Thames River Police.
properties.name: Thames River Police

properties.description: One of Britain's finest churches, built in the Italian Baroque tradition and beautifully restored in 2008. Sustainable features include new heating and management systems and lightwell. RIBA Award Winner 2009. Civic Trust Award Winner 2010.
properties.name: St Martin-in-the-Fields

properties.description: Grade I listed Norman brick-built church consisting of a nave and chancel. Tower at the west end. Gothic-style stone windows from the old church inserted into the present 1636 structure. Rare 17th Century glass was restored in 2020.
properties.name: St Lawrence Church, Morden

properties.description: St John’s has a wide nave approached via a narthex formed under the gallery running the width of the west end.  East of the nave is a chancel flanked to the south by the Lady Chapel and to the north by the organ chamber with loft over.
properties.name: St John the Divine

properties.description: The home of Conway Hall Ethical Society, an organisation renowned as a hub for free speech and progressive thought. Grade II listed building with both Arts and Crafts and Art Deco features adding to its distinctive style.
properties.name: Conway Hall

properties.description: Inigo Jones design 1640 at 59/60 LIF, copied  by 57/58  with portico and elliptical staircase added by Soane.  Refurbished by current occupiers, a barristers' chambers. Retains many original features, staircases, fireplaces and mouldings
properties.name: Garden Court Chambers

properties.description: Tudor almshouses dating from 1596 and founded by the Archbishop of Canterbury John Whitgift. Chapel and Courtyard with original 16C clock.
properties.name: Whitgift Almshouses

properties.description: Guided tours of the largest purpose-built mosque in Western Europe accommodating 13,000 worshippers blending of Islamic and modern British architecture. Recent developments, involving reconstruction after a fire, are nearing completion.
properties.name: Baitul Futuh Mosque

properties.description: Wonderful example of a repertory theatre in style of European opera houses, with vast stage, sub-stage workshops and auditorium seating 785.
properties.name: Churchill Theatre

properties.description: As per Grand Designs, the opening roof, the retracting loo and sliding bed-bath typify this extraordinary response to constraints of a tight budget on a brownfield site. Shortlisted RIBA Awards 2006. One of nation's favourite TV houses.
properties.name: 15 and a half Consort Road

properties.description: London's main tourist information centre is clad in a specially manufactured system of 220 pre-finished stainless steel panels. The subtly reflective surface provides a striking counterpoint to St Paul's. NOTE: Closed on Monday 19 September
properties.name: City Information Centre

properties.description: The independent cultural centre Pushkin House will contribute to this year's Open House Festival through a programme of events and community initiatives at its Grade-II listed building in Bloomsbury Square.
properties.name: Pushkin House

properties.description: Refurbished extended building, a centre for film and photography. Central courtyard integrated 'hub' allows light and air to filter through. Loft conversion to create studio and work space. Sustainable features include sedum roof.
properties.name: Four Corners

properties.description: LMA's older building was built in the late 1930s for the Temple Press and has many original features.   Purpose built extension in early 1990s for archival storage. Public rooms remodelled by Bisset Adams in 2000s.
properties.name: London Metropolitan Archives

properties.description: The home of the Royal Astronomical Society since 1874, refurbished in 2007. Part of the extension to Burlington House to provide accommodation for learned societies.
properties.name: Burlington House: Royal Astronomical Society

properties.description: Iconic brutalist building in the heart of Thamesmead, renovation led by Bow Arts Trust in partnership with Peabody, supported by the Mayor’s London Regeneration Fund (LEAP). The centre has opened as a cultural hub for Thamesmead.
properties.name: Lakeside Centre

properties.description: Built thanks to a generous gift from local benefactress, Mrs Lavinia Keene, St Patrick's was consecrated in July 1940 and is unusual in style. The concrete and brick interior contrasts with the dramatic, colourful reredos. Grade II listed.
properties.name: St Patrick's Church

properties.description: Ruskinian walk from RIBA award-winning Chiswick Business Park, Gunnersbury Triangle Nature Reserve through South Acton Estate, birthplace of artist Patrick Caulfield; Woodlands Park Ice House; to home of Wm Willett, of Daylight Saving Time
properties.name: A Ruskinian Walk Through Shared Heritage

properties.description: Home to the oldest geological society in the world, founded in 1807. The Society has been based at Burlington House since 1874, and now has over 12,000 members worldwide.
properties.name: Burlington House: The Geological Society of London

properties.description: Grade II listed church with fine collection of Pre-Raphaelite stained glass windows by Morris & Co. including Burne Jones and Rossetti. Wall paintings. Mosaic reredos. Minchenden Oak  - ancient pollarded oak more than 800 years old.
properties.name: Christ Church Southgate and the Minchenden Oak Garden

properties.description: St John's Gate in Clerkenwell dates from 1504 and was built for the Knights Hospitaller. 19th and early 20th century additions by Richard Norman Shaw and John Oldrid Scott. Grade I listed. Home to the Museum of the Order of St John.
properties.name: Museum of the Order of St John

properties.description: A unique striking playscape and adobe home structure that integrates outside learning with innovative earth forms. Construction is 'rammed' earth made from earth filled tubes. Adobe construction is recognised for sound reducing properties.
properties.name: Adobe Village Hounslow Heath Infant and Nursery School

properties.description: Some of London's best Roman remains, comprising late 2C house with a 3C bath house built within its courtyard. First discovered in 1848.
properties.name: Billingsgate Roman House & Baths

properties.description: Medieval Parish Church, 15C, enlarged & rebuilt in 19C. Shingle spire 1857, by Wollaston. Chancel by Ferrey, lengthened with East wall by Bodley & Garner. Scadbury Chapel (Walsingham tombs), with rood screen. Clock by Dent, 1858.
properties.name: St Nicholas Church, Chislehurst

properties.description: Designed by the world renowned Zaha Hadid Architects, Roca London Gallery is a unique space where water acts as the architectural theme. Guests can also visit 'Everything Flows', a major exhibition exploring the work of Zaha Hadid Design.
properties.name: Roca London Gallery

properties.description: A historic living parish church, progressively shaped from the Tudor to the Edwardian period. St Mary's has recently undergone a major refurbishment and the newly restored windows recapture the original airiness of the C18 nave.
properties.name: St Mary Magdalene

properties.description: Barking town centre has seen significant development over recent years with substantial growth in housing and infrastructure. These guided tours will visit existing award winning schemes and set out the vision for the future of the town.
properties.name: Barking Town Centre Tour

properties.description: Former Midland Grand Hotel, now St Pancras Renaissance Hotel and Chambers apartments. Includes hotel lobby and clock tower.
properties.name: St Pancras Chambers and Clock Tower

properties.description: The building features a limestone exterior designed to 'complement but not mimic' the surrounding historical architecture, whilst behind the façade is a 4-storey composition of steel, glass and exposed concrete.
properties.name: University of Greenwich, Stockwell Street

properties.description: A cleverly integrated mixture of architectural styles and periods, incorporating a late 1720s house (later home to Herbert Henry Asquith) and the purpose-built College of Nursing (1926). Access to main building via guided tour only.
properties.name: Royal College of Nursing

properties.description: St Anne's Limehouse has been described as 'the finest parish church in England.' Designed by Nicholas Hawksmoor, it is Grade I listed and one of the Major Churches in the Church of England. It is home to a thriving Christian congregation.
properties.name: St Anne's Church, Limehouse

properties.description: Celebrating it's 50th year this year Dawson's Heights is split between 2 blocks consisting of 296 flats, all with private balconies. A fantastic example of beautifully designed social housing with uninterrupted views of the London skyline.
properties.name: Dawson's Heights

properties.description: The NOW Gallery is an art space - contained within two curved glass pavilions linked by a patinated brass-edged canopy - which defines the southern edge of Peninsula Square and acts as a gateway to the south, the cable car and Central Park.
properties.name: NOW Gallery

properties.description: Dutch bank ING moved its UK office to this special building in 2016.  The building blends a historic exterior (including its original Portland stone façade) with a modern 135,220 sqft of office space. City Heritage Award winner 2015.
properties.name: 8-10 Moorgate

properties.description: The award-winning Leadenhall Building was designed by international architects RSHP in 2014. L14 became the practice's headquarters in 2015. The Studio is a completely open plan office, reflecting the democratic beliefs of the practice.
properties.name: RSHP at The Leadenhall Building

properties.description: Centre of German religious and cultural life for more than 200 years. Impressive 20th century church building with contributions from various German artists. Exhibition of German émigré artist Hans Feibusch „Five Stories from the Old Testament“ (courtesy of Ben Uri Gallery). Demonstration of the organ by resident organist Paul Dichtl.
properties.name: St Bonifatius RC German Church

properties.description: Baroque palace built for King William III and Mary II. The original Tudor towers and chimneys were replaced by grand and elegant exteriors that dominate the buildings today.
properties.name: Royal School of Needlework

properties.description: The operational factory of Kaymet, a maker of trays and trolleys since 1947. A hidden 1950s building with a small yard, originally a printing works. It is brick built, with clear-storey glazing and tubular truss north-light main shed roof.
properties.name: Kaymet Factory

properties.description:
Victorian Potting sheds converted to artists' studios set within the grounds of Grade II listed Cannizaro Park.
The eight resident artists will be displaying their work during the festival at these unique studios.
properties.name: Cannizaro Studios

properties.description: Built in the Georgian style, the Guildhall brought together Kingston's administrative functions. Purpose-built Magistrates Courts were included in the building, part of which are now home to Kingston History Centre.
properties.name: Kingston Guildhall and History Centre

properties.description: Archaeologist Anthony Thomas leads a tour on the history of Lesnes Abbey.
properties.name: Lesnes Abbey Tour

properties.description: One of the finest examples of Georgian architecture. It has been hardly altered since built. The church is a rectangular building of Portland stone, with a projecting chancel. Two external walls were restored in 2019. Grade I listed
properties.name: St Mary The Virgin Wanstead

properties.description: The Gilbert & George Centre was originally established as a registered charity by the artist in 2009 with the objective to advance the education of the public in the arts, and generally to advance the arts, architecture, heritage, and culture for the benefit of the public.
properties.name: Gilbert & George Centre

properties.description:
Join us for a free guided tour of the RPS Museum and Library and find out what crocodiles have to do with pharmacy!
Over 180 years old, the RPS Museum and Library is a hidden gem in East London, full of the weird and wonderful world of pharmacy history.
Find out how best to use bear’s grease and explore a collection of poisons even Agatha Christie would swoon at!

Scroll down to find out more
properties.name: Royal Pharmaceutical Society Museum

properties.description: The Aga Khan Centre, designed by Pritzker prize winning architect Fumihiko Maki, houses the UK institutions of the Aga Khan Development Network. A unique feature are its six gardens inspired by different regions of the Muslim world.
properties.name: Aga Khan Centre

properties.description: A walk from Barbican Underground Station via the Museum of London to Barbican and then to Golden Lane.
properties.name: Imagine Golden Lane at Net Zero - a walking tour

properties.description: Constructed in 1902 as the Will's Library, part of  Guy's Hospital Medical School. Building of red brick  with additional stonework and partially covered in creeper. Internally are carved oak cabinets and ornate columns.
properties.name: King's College London: Museum of Life Sciences

properties.description: St.Margaret's has delivered community activity on Old Ford Road since the start of the 20th century. In 2022, they started working with Tower Hamlets Council to bring activities to Tramshed, Digby St, E2 0LS - where this event will be held.
properties.name: St. Margaret's House

properties.description: Alton Estate is renowned for its mix of high-rise Le Corbusian architecture in Alton West & its low-rise Scandinavian approach to modernism in Alton East. Designed by the London County Council  architects they completed in 1959.
properties.name: Alton Estate

properties.description: The Estorick Collection is housed in a beautiful Georgian building previously known as Northampton Lodge. Today, the museum comprises six galleries over three floors, as well as a library, offices, a café and bookshop.
properties.name: Estorick Collection of Modern Italian Art

properties.description: James Maltby Bignall (1827-1885) worked in the practice of Sir George Gilbert Scott, the architect of St Pancras Station. The style of St Michael's is late Gothic Revival, in its size and height reminiscent of Northern European churches.
properties.name: St Michael and All Angels Church

properties.description: A House for Artists is an ambitious project, designed to provide affordable, sustainable housing for artists, who will offer long-term civic and cultural engagement for communities in Barking Town Centre. Drop in to the creative workshop.
properties.name: A House for Artists

properties.description: Grade II* listed church dating from 12C with Medieval, Tudor, Georgian & Victorian features. 16C Tower. Church refurbishment and new extension in progress in 2022. Over 1300 monuments with four Grade II listed tombs in churchyard.
properties.name: St. Mary's Church, Walthamstow Village

properties.description: Architecture and art produced in an unmodified street of 56 houses, railway arch studios, and private galleries between 1974 and 2022. Beck Rd is an iconic artist haven and its residents key contributors to UK art history.
properties.name: ‘OPEN’ Beyond Beck Road (part II)

properties.description: The carefully renovated Van Gogh House seeks to share its story and inspire a new generation of artists through Van Gogh’s London story. The house curates a dynamic programme of events anchored in the artist’s practice and local heritage.
properties.name: Van Gogh House London

properties.description: Unit used as an art studio in a small industrial estate.
properties.name: Cut Glass Studio Ltd, Tottenham Hale

properties.description: Coopers' Hall is a late 17th century, timber-framed merchant's house with a Georgian frontage. A Livery Hall since 1957, it features a fine Courtoom, dining room and an impressive staircase spiralling up the entire height of the building.
properties.name: Coopers' Hall

properties.description: Pennington Street Warehouse is a Grade II Listed Warehouse, sensitively adapted in 2019 into a vibrant and creative home for architects & masterplanners, JTP.
properties.name: JTP Studios, Pennington Street Warehouse

Explore the world's first dinosaur models hidden in a south London park. The 30 Grade I listed, life-size statues of dinosaurs and other extinct animals at Crystal Palace Park have thrilled
visitors for 166 years. Tour is kids friendly.

Walter Segal System Talk, aimed at people interested in using this building method.
Walters Way Tour (outside only), then to a local charity (AFRIL) community/volunteer build on allotments a few mins walk.
Approx 1 hour.

The House is now open to the public with free entry six days a week. An industrial heritage site that was the hub of one of London’s first major pieces of urban infrastructure.

Join us for an interesting and informative walk around Surbiton with our experienced guide. Find out why Surbiton was called the Queen of the suburbs and plenty more. 

Visit our website: https://www.kingstontourguides.org.uk/

UPDATED: Open daily 10.30am-4pm Closed Mon 19 September.
Combined guided tours of Amphitheatre and Guildhall Art Gallery at 12.15pm & 1.15pm on Tuesdays, Thursdays, Fridays, Saturdays & Sundays.
The capital’s only known Roman Amphitheatre

A great little museum set in the Grade 2 listed Ossulston Estate - a prime example of pre-war Social housing - based on Karl Marz Hof in Vienna.
Open Wednesdays to Saturdays throughout Festival 
Sunday 11th Event

Historical connections
Admiral Fitzroy sailed to Galapagos Islands with Charles Darwin.
